1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. e4 $5 {An interesting move order
aiming at getting similar positions as in the Re1 systems albeit a tempo down.
This is played by those who fear that Black would play ...Be7 instead of ...
a7-a6 and answer Re1 with ...d5 or ...Ne4.} Bb7 6. d3 d6 7. Bg2 g6 $5 {Since
the bishop will eventually land on g7, Black has good reasons to allow this at
once.} ({With the given move order Black can avoid the line} 7... Be7 8. O-O {
covered in Chapter 12.}) 8. O-O (8. b3 {leads to a slow strategic battle in
which Black's chances are not worse.} Bg7 9. Bb2 (9. O-O O-O 10. Bb2 Nc6 11. a3
Nd7 12. Rb1 Qe7 13. Ne1 Nd4 14. f4 Rae8 15. b4 Qd8 16. Nf3 f5 $11 {Tseitlin,M 
(2430)-Dizdarevic,E (2510) Moscow 1989 (½-½, 52)}) 9... a6 10. O-O O-O 11.
Qd2 (11. Re1 e5 12. Nd5 Nc6 $10) 11... Nc6 12. Nh4 Nd7 (12... e5 $5) 13. f4 Rb8
14. Rad1 Re8 15. Ne2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 e5 $1 17. Bh3 (17. f5 Qg5 18. Qd2 Qxd2 19.
Rxd2 g5 20. Nf3 g4 21. Ne1 Nf6 $15) (17. Nf3 $5 exf4 $140 18. gxf4 b5) 17...
exf4 18. Nxf4 Nd4 19. Nf3 (19. Bxd7 $5 Qxd7 20. Nf3 $10) 19... Nxf3+ 20. Rxf3
Ne5 21. Rf2 b5 22. cxb5 axb5 23. d4 cxd4 24. Qxd4 Qc7 $1 25. Qxd6 Qc3 $1 26.
Nd5 Bxd5 27. Qxd5 Qe3 $1 $44 {with excellent play on dark squares, Smejkal,J 
(2535)-Portisch,L (2650) Moscow 1981 (0-1, 58)}) 8... Bg7 9. Re1 ({The plan
based on} 9. Ne1 {makes less sense with the bishop on g7, as Black's king will
be safely defended:} Nc6 10. Nc2 (10. f4 O-O 11. g4 a6 12. g5 Nh5 13. Bf3 f5
14. Bxh5 gxh5 15. Qxh5 Nd4 {[%cal Gb6b5] followed by ...b6-b5 with excellent
counterplay.}) 10... O-O 11. Bg5 a6 12. Qd2 Re8 13. Bh6 Bh8 14. h3 Nd4 15. Nxd4
cxd4 16. Ne2 Nd7 17. g4 b5 {½-½ Portisch,L (2655)-Ribli,Z (2610) Tilburg 1980
}) (9. Rb1 O-O (9... Nc6 10. d4 e5 {is entirely possible, too.}) 10. b4 (10.
Nh4 Nc6 11. f4 a6 12. Be3 Rb8 13. h3 b5 14. Kh2 Nd4 15. Qd2 Qa5 16. b3 Nd7 {
and Black has already light initiative Milov,V (2659)-Van Wely,L (2650) Lugo
2009 (0-1, 36)}) 10... Nc6 11. a3 Rb8 12. Bd2 a6 13. b5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Ne8 15.
Qc1 Nc7 16. Nc3 Ba8 17. Bh6 e5 18. Bg5 {Rohde,M (2497)-Yudasin,L (2563)
Philadelphia 2002 (0-1, 50)} f6 19. Bd2 Ne6 $11) 9... O-O 10. d4 cxd4 ({
Once again Black can think of keeping the tension with} 10... Nc6 11. e5 Nd7
12. Bg5 Qb8 {with unclear play.}) 11. Nxd4 a6 12. b3 (12. Bg5 {eventually
yielded White an advantage but this was due to Black's hesitations:} Qc7 13.
Qd2 Nbd7 (13... Qxc4 14. Rac1) (13... Ng4 $5 14. h3 h6 15. hxg4 hxg5 16. Rac1
Nd7 17. Nf3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Qxg5 Rad8 {with excellent play on the dark
squares for the pawn.}) 14. h3 Rac8 15. Rad1 Qb8 (15... Qxc4 $5 16. e5 dxe5 17.
Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Bxb7 Rc7 $11) 16. Nc2 (16. b3 Rfe8 17. Nc2 b5 $1 {with good
counterplay for instance} 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nxb5 Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Rxe4
Qxb5 $17) 16... Rxc4 17. Qxd6 Qa8 (17... Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Nc5 19. Rxb6 Nfd7 20.
Rd6 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rxc3 22. Nd4 $14) 18. Ne3 Rxc3 19. bxc3 Bxe4 $14 {Romanishin,
O (2585)-Averkin,O (2450) Sochi 1982 (1-0, 37)}) (12. e5 $2 {does not work due
to} Bxg2 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. Kxg2 Qxd4) 12... Nbd7 13. Ba3 $5 {Trying to prove
that ...Bg7 was premature.} ({Here is an example of how to outplay White in
the long run:} 13. Bb2 Qc7 14. Re2 Rad8 15. Qe1 Rfe8 16. Rd1 Qb8 17. f3 Ba8 18.
Kh1 Nc5 19. Ba1 h5 20. Bb2 h4 21. g4 g5 22. Bc1 Nh7 23. h3 Qc7 24. Be3 Qe7 25.
Nc2 Be5 26. Bd4 a5 27. Bxe5 dxe5 28. Red2 Nf8 29. Rxd8 Rxd8 30. Rxd8 Qxd8 31.
Qd1 Qxd1+ 32. Nxd1 Ng6 33. Nce3 Nf4 $17 {Gheorghiu,F (2520)-Portisch,L (2630)
Valetta 1980 (½-½, 57)}) 13... Nc5 14. b4 Ncd7 15. b5 $5 Ne8 $1 (15... Ne5
16. Nc6 (16. Qb3 Nfd7 (16... Rc8 17. Rad1 Nxc4 18. e5 $1 $16 {Ding}) 17. Bxd6
Nc5 18. Bxc5 bxc5 19. Nf3 axb5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. cxb5 c4 22. Qb2 Qa5 $44) 16...
Bxc6 17. Bxd6 {Kramnik}) 16. Rc1 Ne5 17. Qe2 axb5 (17... Rc8 18. bxa6 Bxa6 19.
Ncb5) (17... g5 $5) 18. Ndxb5 g5 $1 {The start of a brilliant plan.} 19. h3 (
19. Rcd1 g4 {offers Black perfect stability.}) 19... f5 $1 20. exf5 (20. Bb4 f4
$17) (20. f4 gxf4 21. gxf4 Ng6 $17) 20... Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxa3 22. Nxa3 Qa8+ 23.
Qe4 Qxa3 24. fxe6 Nf6 25. Qe2 Qa8+ 26. f3 h5 27. e7 Re8 28. Ne4 g4 $17 {
Ding Liren (2769)-Kramnik,V (2800) Berlin (Candidates) 2018 (½-½, 47)} *

