1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {This can lead to several
important systems from other openings, but there is one plan with independent
value.} d5 $5 (5... Bb4 6. g3 {transposes to the fianchetto Nimzovitsch, with
rather one-sided play.}) (5... Nc6 {transposes to an important tabiya of the
symmetrical English.}) ({I frequently played} 5... a6 6. g3 ({The problem is
that White can transpose to a completely different opening with} 6. e4 {
, with lots of theory.}) 6... Qc7 7. Qd3 Nc6 8. Nxc6 Qxc6 $11) 6. cxd5 {
One of the two main continuations.} ({With the knight exposed on c3} 6. g3 $2 {
is simply bad:} e5 7. Nf3 d4 8. Nxe5 Qd6 9. Qa4+ (9. Nb5 Qxe5 10. a3 {
Threatening Bf4 without fearing ...Bb4+.} Na6 $1 $17) 9... Nbd7 10. Nxd7 (10.
Nb5 Qb4+ $1) 10... Bxd7 11. Nb5 Qc6 12. Rg1 a6 13. Bg2 Qc8 $17 {Govciyan,P 
(2438)-Salaun,Y (2329) Paris 2009 (0-1, 26)}) (6. e3 {is too soft to cause
problems.} a6 {Preventing a later Bb5 and waiting for White to develop his
bishop before playing ...dxc4.} (6... Nc6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. O-O Bd6 {
is also playable as in Carlsen,M (2832)-Grischuk,A (2750) chess.com (blitz)
2017 (½-½, 56)}) 7. cxd5 (7. Be2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Be2 Bb7 {offers Black
very comfortable play.}) 7... Nxd5 ({Playing with an isolated queen pawn is
entirely viable:} 7... exd5 8. Be2 Bd6 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. O-O O-O 12.
Nxd5 Nxd4 13. exd4 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bb5 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qf3 Qh4 17. g3 Bxe2 18.
Qxe2 Qxd4 $11 {Gavrikov,V (2525)-Kaidanov,G (2475) Lvov 1987 (½-½, 23)}) 8.
Bd2 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O e5 $5 {This typical move makes a lot of sense after
White's passive play.} 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Rc1 Ndb4 13. Ne1 Qd7 14. a3 Rd8 15. Nf3
Nd3 16. Rc2 Qc7 17. Bxd3 Rxd3 18. Qe2 Rd8 19. Rd1 Be6 $15 {Todorov,Y-Arnaudov,
P (2347) Plovdiv 2009 (0-1, 48)}) ({For} 6. Bg5 {see Chapter 3.}) (6. Bf4 {
has enjoyed some popularity later but Black has more than one way to parry the
threat Ndb5.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] A simple developing move threatening ...e6-e5.
} (6... Nc6 7. Ndb5 e5 8. cxd5 {leads to a heavily analyzed symmetrical
English main line.}) 7. Qa4 (7. Nf3 Bb4 {offers Black easy development.}) (7.
Bg5 e5 8. Nf3 d4 {basically gains a tempo over the 6.Bg5 lines.}) (7. Ndb5 {
has a similar effect after} e5 8. Bg5 a6 9. Qa4 Rb8 $17) 7... Bc5 8. cxd5 O-O
9. Nb3 exd5 (9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. e3 Nb6 12. Qa5 Be7 13. Nd4 Bf6 $11 14.
Rd1 Bg4 $5) (9... Nb6 10. Qa5 Nbxd5 11. Qxc5 Nxf4 12. Rd1 {Popov,V (2595)
-Sharafiev,A (2400) Ulan Ude 2009 (1-0, 32)} Bd7 $11) 10. e3 Nb6 11. Qa5 {
Bu,X (2705)-Grischuk,A (2737) Doha (blitz) 2016 (½-½, 38)} Be7 12. Nd4 Nc4
13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. O-O-O Bd7 $11) 6... Nxd5 {The position is more or less
symmetrical and developing is the highest priority for both players.} 7. Bd2 {
White hopes that activating his bishop after an exchange on c3 could yield him
the initiative. I have chosen just one of the playable lines for Black.} Nf6 $5
{Hightlighting the drawbacks of the last move.} 8. Nb3 (8. Bf4 {Romanov,E 
(2619)-Dubov,D (2648) St Petersburg 2016 (½-½, 38)} Nd5 9. Nxd5 (9. Bd2 $11)
9... Qxd5 10. Nf3 (10. Rc1 Bd7) (10. Nb3 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 a5 12. Bxb4 Qxd1+ 13.
Kxd1 axb4 14. e3 Bd7 15. Bd3 Bc6 16. Ke2 Nd7 17. Rhc1 Ke7 18. f3 Ne5 $11) 10...
Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 f6 12. e4 e5 13. Be3 Be6 14. Nd2 Nc6 15. Bc4 Kf7 $11) (8. e3 Be7
9. Bb5+ Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 Nc5 12. Qc2 e5 13. Nf3 e4 14. Nd4 {Stebbings,
A (2293)-Vaisser,A (2505) Marianske Lazne 2016 (0-1, 88)} Bd7 $1 {Black gains
a tempo for his development as the bishops' exchange would leave d3 weak.})
8... b6 $5 {Probably the best.} (8... Bd7 9. e4 Nc6 10. Be2 {leaves White with
some light initiative, Khismatullin,D (2617)-Dubov,D (2648) Sochi 2016 (0-1,
43)}) (8... a5 $5 9. g3 Bd7 10. Bg2 Bc6 11. O-O a4 12. Nc1 a3 13. Rb1 Be7 14.
bxa3 Rxa3 15. Nb5 Ra8 16. Bf4 O-O $11 {Romanov,E (2610)-Sorokin,A (2469) Sochi
2017 (1-0, 42)}) 9. e4 Bb7 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 11. Qe2 a6 12. Bd3 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14.
Rad1 Qb8 (14... b5 $5) 15. f4 Rd8 16. e5 Nd5 17. Ne4 Nf8 {with a solid
kingside defence and good counterplay in the centre, Tomashevsky,E (2731)
-Nepomniachtchi,I (2740) Moscow 2016 (0-1, 47)} *

