1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg5 {A logical
developing move, adding pressure on Black's center.} e5 {An equally logical
reaction. Black starts the central expansion in a moment when White's kingside
is underdeveloped.} 7. Nf3 {White has tried many other moves here.} (7. Bxf6
gxf6 {is likely to transpose to any of the lines below.}) (7. Nb3 d4 8. Nd5 (8.
Bxf6 gxf6 {allows Black to put even more pawns into motion.} 9. Nd5 f5 10. g3
Nc6 11. Bg2 Bg7 12. e3 a5 {with space advantage and initiative compensated by
the strong central knight.}) 8... Nbd7 (8... Be7 $5 {is also interesting.} 9.
Nxe7 Qxe7 10. e3 Nc6 11. Be2 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. exd4 exd4 {Black's pawn is
more of a strength than a weakness.} 14. O-O O-O 15. Nc5 Bf5 16. Nd3 Rfe8 17.
Re1 Qg6 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. Nd5 d3 20. Bf1 Nd4 $17 {Ortega,L (2440)-Tal,M (2600)
Yerevan 1986 (0-1, 27)}) 9. e3 h6 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. c5 Bd7 13.
Bd3 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. exd4 exd4 16. Be4 Rab8 17. Rc1 Rfc8 18. g3 {½-½
Schinke,A (2473)-Walter,G (2388) ICCF email 2012} a5 $11) (7. Ndb5 {is at
least risky.} a6 8. Qa4 Bd7 9. cxd5 (9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. cxd5 Bxb5 11. Nxb5 axb5
12. Qxb5+ Nd7 $19 {with virtually no compensation for the piece, due to
White's poor development and king's exposure, Reshevsky,S (2460)-Christiansen,
L (2550) Los Angeles 1984 (0-1, 22)}) (9. O-O-O {0-1 (61) Rubinstein,
S-Gruenfeld,E Vienna 1933} d4) 9... Bxb5 ({Stronger than} 9... Qb6 10. Be3 $1
Bxb5 11. Bxb6 Bxa4 12. Nxa4 Bb4+ 13. Kd1 $11 {Savon,V-Krogius,N Tbilisi 1966 
(½-½, 26)}) 10. Nxb5 axb5 11. Qxa8 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+ $1 (13...
Qxd5+ $2 {helps White to develop his initiative:} 14. Ke1 O-O 15. Rd1 $16 {
Mikhalchishin,A (2545)-Gorelov,S (2420) Volgodonsk 1981 (½-½, 41)}) 14. Ke1
Qb6 $3 15. e3 (15. Qxb8+ Kd7 16. Qxh8 Qa5+ {mates.}) 15... O-O 16. Qa3 Qf6 17.
f3 Qh4+ 18. g3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Qxh1 20. e4 Qh2 $15) (7. Nc2 d4 8. Nd5 Be6 9. Bxf6
(9. e4 Be7 $11) 9... gxf6 10. e4 f5 11. Bd3 Nd7 $11 {with a complex strategic
struggle and excellent play for Black.}) 7... d4 8. Bxf6 (8. Nd5 Be7 9. Bxf6
Bxf6 10. g3 (10. e3 dxe3 11. Nxe3 O-O 12. Bd3 Nc6 {doesn't cause Black
problems, either.}) 10... Be6 11. Qb3 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Bh3
Nb6 15. d6 O-O $15 {[%csl Rd6,Re1] Georgiev,K (2595)-Gurevich,D (2475) Saint
John 1988 (1-0, 42) The d6-pawn is vulnerable and the king is temporarily
stuck in the centre.}) 8... gxf6 {Now and in other similar lines above the
double pawns are not weak, as they are mobile. Compare with the old Sveshnikov
mainlines.} 9. Nd5 Be6 10. e4 {White is best adviced to prepare the kingside
development.} (10. Qb3 $6 Qa5+ 11. Nd2 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nd7 13. e4 (13. a3 O-O-O
14. e3 Kb8 {also offers Black the initiative.}) 13... Bb4 14. Qd3 a6 15. a3 {
Biza,M (1864)-Mieres,P (1914) Valasska Bystrice 2013 (0-1, 44)} Nc5 16. Qc2
Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Nb3+ {wins the a1-rook.}) 10... Nd7 (10... dxe3 {
is a worthy alternative:} 11. fxe3 Nc6 12. Be2 Qa5+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2
O-O-O {[%csl Ge6,Gf8] with mutual weaknesses but a strong black bishops' pair.}
) 11. Bd3 ({Once again starting queenside operations is risky:} 11. Qa4 b5 ({
It may be better to prepare this pawn break with} 11... Bd6 $5 12. Bd3 b5 $5
13. Qxb5 O-O {[%cal Gd7c5] followed by ...Nc5.}) 12. cxb5 (12. Qxb5 {[%csl Rd7]
would be better as the d7-knight will be pinned for a while.} Rb8 13. Qa4 Rxb2
14. Bd3 Bd6 {with complicated play.}) 12... Nb6 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Qd1 Bb4+ 15.
Nd2 {Glotov,V-Nikitinyh,B Kharkov 1977 (0-1, 19)} f5 $17 {White is likely to
lose stablity in the centre.}) 11... Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 O-O-O 14. Nh4
Nc5 15. f3 b5 $5 16. b3 (16. cxb5 f5 {shatters White's stability in the centre.
}) 16... bxc4 17. Bxc4 Kb7 18. g3 Bh6+ 19. Kc2 Rd6 $11 {Helmer,J (2028)-Rufu,R
(2002) LSS email 2011 (½-½, 38)} *

