1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 $5 {The same as with 4.d4, this can
transpose to several other systems than the Hedgehog. Once again, choosing
between them is a matter of taste.} b6 $5 {This keeps the Hedgehog contours
only temporarily. It is actually going to transpose to the 4.e3 Queen's Indian,
a solid but not too threatening opening.} ({For many years I had} 4... g6 {
in my repertoire. Black aims at transposing to some sort of reversed Reti, but
there is an early problem with this move order:} 5. d4 Bg7 6. dxc5 (6. Be2 O-O
7. O-O d6 {is more or less what Black would be glad to achieve.}) 6... Na6 7.
e4 $1 Nxc5 8. Qd4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4] followed by g2-g4 with overwhelming
space advantage.}) (4... d5 5. d4 {would transpose to a symmetrical
Semi-Tarrasch, an opening where due to his extra tempo White has some chances
to achieve a one-sided advantage.}) 5. d4 cxd4 (5... Bb7 $2 6. d5 $16 {[%csl
Rb7] would lead to a very passive Benoni version, as Black has invested two
tempi to place his bishop on a dead diagonal.}) 6. exd4 Bb7 ({One more
deviation is} 6... Bb4 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O O-O ({I would also consider} 8... Bxc3
9. bxc3 d6 {followed by ...Qc7, ...Nbd7.}) 9. Na4 {reaching a classical
Nimzowitsch Indian tabiya.}) 7. Bd3 ({If} 7. d5 Bb4 {White cannot maintain his
space advantage.}) (7. a3 {[%cal Gd4d5] already threatens d4-d5, aiming at
provoking ...d6-d5 in a moment when Black's kingside is underdeveloped.} d6 $5
{Despite the engines' initial skepticism I find this plan solid enough. It
mainly works because White has spent a tempo on a2-a3.} (7... Be7 8. d5 {
causes problems.}) (7... d5 8. Ne5 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf1b5]} a6 {Taking measures
against cxd5 and Bb5+.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Qf3 {This was played in a few games
and it offers White some early initiative.} Qe7 11. Ne4 Qc7 {Rohde,M (2555)
-Gurevich,D (2470) Philadelphia 1990 (1-0, 52)} 12. Ng5 $5 Nb4 13. Qxf7+ Qxf7
14. Nexf7 Nc2+ 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Nxh8 Bd5 17. Nxh7) 8. Bd3 (8. d5 e5 9. Bd3 g6
10. O-O Bg7 {The b7-bishop is temporarily passive but it inhibits c4-c5. At
the same time, Black's kingside majority may become threatening.} 11. Bg5 h6 12.
Bh4 Nbd7 13. Nd2 O-O 14. Nde4 {½-½ Levin,F (2476)-Zaragatski,I (2498)
Netherlands 2011} g5 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Bg3 Qe7 17. Bf5 Bc8 {and it seems that
White cannot maintain the blockade:} 18. b4 {preventing ..Nc5.} Nf6 19. Qc2 $6
Bxf5 20. Qxf5 Rac8 21. Qd3 e4 22. Qe2 Nd7 $15) 8... g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Re1 O-O
11. b4 Nbd7 12. Bb2 Re8 13. Bf1 a6 14. Qd3 e5 15. d5 Nh5 {with counterplay
Bruno,F (2414)-Rombaldoni,A (2530) Rome 2013 (0-1, 47)}) (7. Be2 {looks more
modest but is not completely without poison. The safest move order is} Be7 (
7... d5 8. Ne5 {reveals White's intentions: he not only threatens Qa4+ but
also plans to increase the pressure in the center with Bf3.} dxc4 9. O-O Be7
10. Bf3 Qc8 11. Qa4+ Nfd7 {Keeping c6 defended.} 12. d5 {with initiative.}) (
7... Bb4 $5 {could transpose to a Nimzoindian where the bishop is slightly
passive on e2.}) 8. O-O (8. d5 {runs into} Bb4 {even though this basically
wastes a tempo. The point is that Black ensures his stability on dark squares
and, at the same time, puts pressure on d5, too.} 9. Nd4 O-O 10. O-O Bxc3 11.
bxc3 Na6 $13) 8... d5 9. Ne5 (9. cxd5 Nxd5 {does not offer White the same kind
of activity as in the main line with the bishop on d3.}) 9... O-O 10. Bf3 Nc6
11. Re1 Rc8 12. cxd5 Nxe5 13. Rxe5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 {½-½ Speelman, J (2555)
-Gurevich,D (2535) Beersheba 1987} Bxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 $11) 7... Be7 ({Since
White has not spent a tempo on a useless pawn move,} 7... d6 {may be riskier
than above.} 8. d5 e5 9. O-O g6 10. c5 $5 bxc5 11. Bb5+ Nfd7 {Ilampoornan,R 
(1860)-Batsuren,D (2350) Ahmedabad 2017 (0-1, 54)} 12. Bg5 f6 13. Ne4) 8. O-O (
8. d5 {is not too molesting now:} exd5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. O-O Nc6
12. Re1 Be6 {Black has an extra pawn and a solid position.}) (8. Bg5 {is an
active developing move, implying some commitment, though, as after Black's
natural reply White will have to exchange his bishop or place it slightly away
from the main paths.} h6 9. Bxf6 (9. Bh4 d6 {This flexible (typical Hedgehog)
setup is entirely viable once the dark-squared bishop has left the attacking
c1-h6 diagonal.} (9... Bxf3 $5 10. Qxf3 Nc6 11. Ne2 O-O 12. O-O d5 $11) 10. O-O
Nbd7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Bg3 {This looks a bit hurried,
but in perspective Black could have considered playing ...Nh5 anyway.} Nh5 15.
b4 a6 16. a3 Ndf6 {Black's position is solid, flexible and easier to play
already.} 17. Nd2 Bf8 18. Nce4 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 Re7
22. Qd3 Rec7 $15 {Gausel,E (2480)-Pigusov,E (2584) Ohrid 2001 (½-½, 43)})
9... Bxf6 10. Be4 {AIming to exchange one of the active bishops.} ({If} 10. O-O
{Black can continue developing normally but also try the simplifying} Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 Nc6 12. d5 Ne5 13. Qe4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O 15. Rac1 Re8 16. b3 Bxc3 17. Rxc3
{Palos,O (2350)-Roeder,M (2365) Porz 1989 (½-½, 20)} Qf6 $5 18. Rc2 Rac8 $11)
10... d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Bc2 {The structure has become typical for the
Tartakower Queen's Gambit (after for instance ...c7-c5xd4 or e3-e4xd5).} Qe7+ (
{It is hard to resist giving this check, of course, but I would prefer} 12...
O-O {when White does not have the time for h2-h4 as ...Re8+ would be more
constructive than ...Qe7+. And after} 13. O-O Nc6 {Black has an entirely
normal position.}) 13. Kf1 O-O 14. h4 Qd7 (14... h5 {is more precise with a
possible transposition to the game.}) 15. Rh3 Ba6+ 16. Kg1 Nc6 17. Qd2 Rad8 18.
Rd1 Rfe8 19. Rg3 Kh8 20. Bb1 (20. h5 {forces Black to a weird regrouping which
may be OK though.} Qe7 21. Bb1 Qf8 22. Qc2 Qg8 23. a3 Na5 $132) 20... h5 21. a3
Bc4 22. Bc2 (22. Qc2 g6) 22... Re7 23. b3 Ba6 24. b4 Bc4 $132 {Winants,L (2530)
-Bologan,V (2666) Turin 2006 (0-1, 63)}) 8... d5 9. b3 {This leads to a
classical 4.e3 Queen's Indian tabiya.} (9. Bg5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O {transposes
to a Semi-Tarrasch IQP but with an extra tempo for Black!} 11. Qd3 (11. Qe2 Nc6
12. Rad1 Nb4 13. Ne5 Rc8 (13... Nbd5 {is premature due to} 14. Rd3 $1) 14. f4 (
14. a3 Nbd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bc1 Nf6 17. Rfe1 Rc7 18. Be3 Qa8 19. f3 Nd5 20.
Bd2 {½-½ Nei,I-Szabo,L Beverwijk 1966}) (14. Nxf7 {does not seem too
dangerous:} Rxf7 15. Bxe6 Nbd5) (14. Rfe1 Nfd5 15. Bc1 {Stryjecki,M (2442)
-Kaszowski,D (2327) Lubniewice 2002 (½-½, 25)} Nxc3 16. bxc3 Nd5 17. Bd2 Bg5
{and White has problems keeping his center together.}) 14... Nfd5 15. Bxe7 Nxe7
(15... Qxe7 {may be more solid}) 16. Nxf7 Rxf7 17. Bxe6 {Baczynskyj,B (2350)
-Fishbein,A (2435) Boston 1988 (0-1, 40)} Ned5 {and Black is quite stable on
the light squares.}) 11... Nc6 12. a3 {If it was White's turn to move this
would be exactly a Semi-Tarrasch tabiya. The way it is, he does not have time
to complete his regrouping with Rad1 and Rfe1.} Rc8 (12... Na5 13. Ba2 Bxf3 14.
Qxf3 Qxd4 {is premature due to} 15. b4 {when Black is hanging.}) 13. Rad1 ({
White defends his central pawn as if} 13. Rfe1 {Black can already embark the
plan mentioned above:} Na5 14. Ba2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxd4 16. Rad1 Qc5 17. Bxf6
Bxf6 18. Ne4 Qe7 19. b4 Nc4 $15 {Mortensen,E (2420)-Berg,K (2375) Denmark 1986
(½-½, 83)}) 13... Na5 14. Ba2 Nd5 {With a rook on e1 this would cause
problems, but in our line Black is absolutely safe:} 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxe7
Qxe7 17. Nxd5 exd5 $11) ({For} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 {see Chapter 5}) 9... O-O 10. Bb2 {
After b2-b3 it makes little sense to develop the bishop elsewhere, as his
queenside has been weakened.} (10. Be3 Ne4 (10... Nbd7 11. Qc2 dxc4 12. bxc4
Bxf3 13. gxf3 e5 {Cvitan,O (2410)-Short,N (2475) Baku 1983 (½-½, 64)}) 11.
Rc1 Nd7 12. Qe2 Rc8 13. Rfd1 f5 14. Bf4 g5 15. Be5 g4 16. Ne1 Nxe5 17. Bxe4 (
17. dxe5 Nxf2 $1 18. Kxf2 Bc5+ 19. Kf1 Qg5 {[%cal Gg5f4] The threat ...Qf4+ is
decisive.} 20. g3 f4) 17... dxe4 18. dxe5 Qc7 19. Nb5 Qxe5 20. Rd7 Bg5 21. Rcd1
Bc6 22. Rxa7 Rcd8 23. h4 Rxd1 24. Qxd1 Rd8 25. Qc2 Bd2 {0-1 Bogoljubow,
E-Botvinnik, M Nottingham 1936}) 10... Nc6 {I have played this kind of position
with White many times, usually transposing from the Zukertort move order. But
I eventually came to the conclusion that the lines with Nc3 expose White's
center and switched to those with Nbd2 instead.} 11. Rc1 {This is the main
line.} (11. Qe2 {can be met in a similar way as the main continuation:} Nb4 12.
Bb1 dxc4 13. bxc4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 (14. gxf3 {is relatively better, but not that
much fun for White.}) 14... Qxd4 15. a3 Na6 16. Qb7 {Apparently White wins a
piece but Black has an unexpected resource..} Bd6 $1 17. Qxa6 Bxh2+ $1 18. Kxh2
Qh4+ 19. Kg1 Ng4 20. Rc1 Qxf2+ 21. Kh1 Qh4+ 22. Kg1 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 Qh1+ 24. Ke2
Qxg2+ 25. Kd3 Rad8+ 26. Nd5 Qxb2 {0-1 Straeter,T (2310)-Van den Doel,E (2607)
Germany 2002}) (11. cxd5 {is inoffensive:} Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bc4 Qh5 14.
Ne5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Nb4 16. f3 Rfd8 17. a3 Nd5 $15 {Avrukh,B (2641)-Smirin,I 
(2650) Netanya 2009 (½-½, 24)}) (11. Re1 {[%csl Ga2] does not change much
with respect to the main line, with the exception of the fact that a2 is
defended.} Nb4 12. Bf1 (12. Be2 Rc8 13. a3 Nc6 {left White vulnerable to ...
Na5, when the weakness induced by a2-a3 is obvious, Kekki, P (2350)-Veingold, A 
(2425) Helsinki 1996 (0-1, 36)}) 12... dxc4 13. bxc4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 (14. Qxf3 $2
Nc2 {wins an exchange.}) 14... Bd6 {White has an advantage in the center, but
his kingside is vulnerable.} 15. Ne4 {Muse,D (2295)-Schulz,R (2265) Berlin
1993 (1-0, 41)} Nxe4 16. fxe4 Qg5+ 17. Bg2 e5 {with excellent play on dark
squares.}) 11... Nb4 12. Bb1 (12. Be2 Ne4 13. a3 {Pragna,N (1989)-Nandhini,S 
(1884) Hyderabad 2007 (½-½, 33)} Nc6 {The move a2-a3 counts not only as a
waste of time (the bishop is supposed to return to d3) but more importantly as
a weakening in view of ...Na5.}) 12... dxc4 13. bxc4 Bxf3 $1 14. Qxf3 (14. gxf3
$15) 14... Qxd4 15. a3 Na6 16. Qb7 Bd6 $1 {The same trick as above. It is
interesting that many games have been played with this system, but in very few
did Black go for this line. Actually strong players stopped playing it a long
time ago, possibly after Keres, a white specialist, mentioned this tactical
possibility in the notes to an old game of his with Taimanov.} 17. Nd1 (17.
Qxa6 Bxh2+ $1) 17... Nc5 $17 {Wageih,K (2362)-Amin,A (2277) Egypt 2012 (½-½,
60)} *

