1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 b6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 Bb7 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O
d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Ne5 {This is the modern treatment of this line. White
tries to start an early kingside attack.} ({In the past there has been some
theoretical discussion after} 10. Bb5+ Bc6 {which was considered the main line.
} 11. Qa4 {will later gain time as the black bishop will have to return to b7,
but the white bishop has also moved quite a lot.} (11. Bc4 O-O 12. Ne5 Bb7 13.
Re1 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 $11 {As a result of White's maneuver the bishop has
been transferred from d3 to c4 without loss of time. But it is hard to believe
this is an improvement, as the only way to avoid simplifying (with the
implicit danger of having two weak pawns in the center) is} 15. Nxf7 Rxf7 16.
Bxe6 Nf8 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. c4 Rc8 19. Qd3 Bf6 $15 {when Black's well
regrouped minor pieces are more effective than the rooks, Aagaard,J (2440)
-Danielsen,H (2490) Copenhagen 1997 (½-½, 47)}) 11... Qd7 12. Ne5 (12. Bxc6
Nxc6 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 14. Ne5 $2 b5 $1 $17) 12... Nxc3 13. Qc2 (13. Qb3 Bxb5
14. Nxd7 Ne2+ 15. Kh1 Nxd4 16. Qc3 Nxd7 17. Rd1 e5 $15) 13... Qd5 ({Here, too,
Black can sacrifice the queen:} 13... Nxb5 14. Nxd7 Kxd7 15. d5 $5 {Trying to
prevent Black from consolidating.} Bxd5 16. Qa4 a6 17. Rd1 Nc6 18. Rxd5+ exd5
19. Qg4+ Kc7 20. Bf4+ Nd6 21. Qxg7 Kb7 22. Bxd6 Bxd6 23. Qxf7+ Ne7 {with
complicated and balanced play.}) 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. bxc3 Rc8 17.
Bd2 O-O $15 {White's early activity has left him with the usual central
weaknesses, Leskovar Raimondi, M (2283)-Bruzon Batista, L (2717) Mar del Plata
2012 (0-1, 69)}) (10. Re1 O-O 11. a3 {leads to some sort of Semi-Tarrasch
Isolani, where Black can develop a bit more flexible, though.} Nd7 ({In the
Semi-Tarrasch the knight stands on c6, but after} 11... Nc6 {the knight would
not only be restricted but also prevent Black from keeping a firm control on
d5:} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Be4 {with chances to grab the initiative.}) 12. Bc2 Rc8
13. Qd3 g6 {is probably safest as it keeps the control on e5.} (13... N7f6 {
releases the control over e5 and requires some accuracy.} 14. Bg5 g6 15. Bh6
Nxc3 ({The natural} 15... Re8 {runs into} 16. Ba4 Bc6 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. Ne5 Rc8
19. Qf3 $16 {with annoying pressure.}) 16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. bxc3 Qc7 {Black will
get a pawn for the exchange. His control on d5, two active bishops and the
relative weakness of the a4 and d4 pawns offer him good compensation. If} 18.
Re3 $2 Nd5 $17) 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Ne4 N5f6 $1 $11 {Olesen,M (2250)-Dokhoian,Y 
(2540) Copenhagen 1991 (0-1, 40)}) 10... O-O 11. Qh5 ({The main alternative is
} 11. Qg4 {Black's safest defence is} f5 12. Qe2 Nc7 $5 {Defending e6 in order
to allow ...Nc6.} 13. Rd1 (13. f4 {only weakens White's position.} Nc6 $15 {
Abergel,T (2499)-Bacrot,E (2691)/Pau 2008 (0-1, 39)}) 13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6
15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Be5 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Rc8 18. Rac1 {Hebden,M (2477)-Gormally,D 
(2462) Dundee 2017 (1-0, 54)} Qf6 19. Ne2 (19. Qxf6 Rxf6 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. Bxb5
Rf7 22. Rc6 Rd8 23. Bc4 Re7 $11 {The mutual weaknesses compensate for each
other.}) 19... Bb7 20. Nf4 Qxe5 21. dxe5 Rfd8 22. h4 Kf7 23. Bc4 Ke7 24. Bb3
Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Nd5 26. Bxd5 Bxd5 27. Nxd5+ exd5 28. Rxd5 Rc1+ 29. Kh2 Rc2 {
with the more pleasant ending already due to the centralized king.}) 11... g6
12. Qh3 ({The consequences of the pinning move} 12. Qf3 {are far from
one-sided, as in some cases the queen is exposed.} Nc6 13. Bh6 {This thematic
move offers Black excellent play for the exchange.} (13. Nxd5 Nxe5 14. dxe5
Qxd5 $11) (13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Be4 Qd7 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 $11 {½-½
Hernandez Onna,R (2373)-Pogorelov,R (2442) Balaguer 2005}) 13... Nxd4 $1 14.
Qe4 (14. Qg3 Bd6 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 17. Qe3 Qg7 18. Rfe1 Bc5 19. Qf4
g5 20. Qd2 a5 21. Be4 Rd8 $11 {Black's strong centralization offers him
entirely adequat compensation, Hartung Nielsen,J-Petersen,S/Denmark 2000 (0-1,
54)}) 14... Bc5 15. Nxd5 (15. Bxf8 {unexpectedly runs into problems:} f5 $1 16.
Qe1 Nf4 $3 {with a decisive attack despite the missing rook, Vaganian,R (2640)
-Naiditsch,A (2611) Pamplona 2004 (0-1, 22)}) 15... Bxd5 16. Qg4 f5 17. Qf4 Be4
18. Rae1 Bxd3 19. Nxd3 Bd6 20. Ne5 Nc6 21. Bxf8 Qxf8 22. Qc4 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Bxe5
24. Qxe6+ Qf7 25. Qxe5 Re8 26. Qb5 f4 27. Rd1 f3 28. gxf3 $11 {½-½
Moskalenko,V (2533)-Rizouk,A (2452) Salou 2005}) 12... Nc6 13. Bh6 {Once again
winning an exchange for reasonable compensation.} (13. Ba6 {leads to plain
equality.} Qc7 14. Nxd5 exd5 $11 15. Bf4 Bxa6 16. Rfc1 Bc4 17. Nxg6 Qc8 18.
Nxe7+ Nxe7 19. Qg3+ Ng6 20. b3 Qf5 21. Bh6 Bd3 $15 {Cori Tello,D (2386)-Marin,
M (2548) Benasque 2012 (0-1, 44)}) (13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rac1 {
Colin,V (2399)-Gharamian,T (2557) France 2007 (½-½, 75)} Nb4 {Black either
wins the d4-pawn or gains the bishops' pair.}) 13... Nxd4 ({I have
experimented with giving up the rook for the other bishop:} 13... Re8 14. Bb5
Nxd4 15. Bxe8 Qxe8 16. Rad1 (16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Rfd1 Nf5 18. Bd2 Nh4 {is also
comfortable for Black.}) 16... Nf5 ({Weakening the enemy queenside structure
with} 16... Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nf5 {is simpler and maybe better.}) 17. Bc1 Rc8 18.
Ne4 $6 ({White's best chance for at least a slight advantage is} 18. Nxd5 Bxd5
19. Ng4 h5 20. Nh6+ Nxh6 21. Bxh6 Bf6 22. b3 Rc2 23. Rd2 Qc6 {But due to his
better coordination and the hanging a2-pawn Black should have normal
compensation. In many cases, his next move would be ...Rc1.}) 18... h5 19. Rfe1
{Dumitrache,D (1600)-Marin,M (1600) Snagov (rapid) 2013 (½-½, 26)} f6 20. Nd3
g5 21. f3 Qg6 $15) 14. Bxf8 Bxf8 15. Nxd5 ({The natural} 15. Rad1 {offers Blck
a tempo to develop his initiative:} Nf4 16. Qg3 Bh6 17. f3 Nxd3 18. Nxd3 (18.
Rxd3 Ba6 $19) 18... Nf5 19. Qh3 Be3+ 20. Kh1 (20. Nf2 $6 Qc7 21. Nce4 Kg7 22.
b3 Rc8 $17) 20... Qe7 21. Rfe1 Rd8 $17) (15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Qxh7+ Bg7 17. Qxg6+
Kf8 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Rfe1 Qf6 {is unclear, ½-½ Hobusch,A (2187)-Adamski,J 
(2281) Germany 2014}) 15... Qxd5 16. Rfe1 (16. Ng4 Bg7 17. Rfe1 f5 18. Ne3 Qd7
19. Nc2 Nf3+ 20. gxf3 Qxd3 {with excellent play, Jussupow,A-Van Wely,L/Ajaccio,
Corsica (rapid) 2007 (1/2, 30)}) (16. Nxf7 Bg7 $1 ({With the queen exposed on
d5} 16... Kxf7 17. Qxh7+ Bg7 18. Qxg6+ Kf8 19. Rfe1 {offers White the
initiative. After the main move the knight cannot escape anyway.}) 17. Rac1
Kxf7 18. Rc7+ Kg8 19. Bc4 Qe4 20. Bd3 Qd5 $11) 16... Bb4 $1 {Immediately
starting the fight against the exposed white rook.} 17. Be4 (17. Re3 Bd2 $1)
17... Qxe5 18. Bxb7 Bxe1 19. Bxa8 Ne2+ 20. Kh1 (20. Kf1 Qb5 21. Kxe1 (21. Qg4
Nd4+ 22. Kg1 Bxf2+ 23. Kh1 Qxb2 $17) 21... Nd4 22. Qg4 22... Qxb2 23. Rd1 23...
Qb4+ 24. Kf1 Qc4+ 25. Kg1 Ne2+ $19) 20... Bxf2 (20... Bd2 $5 {wins the b2-pawn
as} 21. Rb1 Nc1 {makes things even worse for White.}) 21. Rf1 $2 {Running into
an unexpected trick.} ({Naiditsch revealed a few interesting lines after the
better} 21. Qf3 Bh4 22. g3 Bxg3 (22... Bf6 23. Re1 Nd4 24. Rxe5 Nxf3 25. Re3
Nd4 $11) 23. hxg3 Nxg3+ 24. Kg1 Ne2+ 25. Kg2 Qxb2 26. Re1 Nf4+ 27. Kh1 g5 {
with five pawns for the rook and a solid position. Play remains complicated
but chances seem to be roughly equal.}) 21... Bg3 $3 22. Bf3 (22. hxg3 $4 Nxg3+
23. Kg1 Qd4+ 24. Rf2 Ne2+ 25. Kf1 Qd1#) 22... Bxh2 23. Bxe2 Qxe2 24. Qf3 Qxf3
25. Rxf3 Bd6 $15 {Werle,J (2556)-Naiditsch,A (2654)/Dresden 2007 (0-1, 40)} *

