1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. e4 $5 {This is a specialty of Rublevsky.
White mainly aims to transpose to a Sicilian Paulsen Hedgehog. While this is
not necessarily worrying, transposing to a different heavily analyzed system
does not suit our initial intentions.} Nc6 {The most active move taking
measures against the early opening of the center.} (4... d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4
a6 7. Bd3 {transposes to a Sicilian Hedgehog.}) 5. Be2 (5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4
{leads to a comfortable for Black Sicilian tabiya. White's center is under
higher pressure than in the similar lines with ...a7-a6 instead of ...Nc6.} 7.
Nxc6 (7. f3 d5 {offers Black early initiative for instance} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5
O-O $1 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Qh4+ 14. g3 Qh3 $17 {
with a very strong attack against the uncastled king. Gretarsson, A (2313)
-Stefansson,H (2547) Iceland 1999 (0-1, 36).}) 7... dxc6 (7... bxc6 8. Bd3 e5 {
is also entirely playable.}) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 (9. Bd2 e5 $1 {Turning the
d4-square into a weakness.} 10. O-O-O Ke7 11. f3 Rd8 12. a3 Bc5 {was
comfortable for Black in Lenderman, A (2515)-Berg, G (2066) Mineola 2008 (1-0,
31). White has no success in harassing the bishop:} 13. b4 Bf2 14. Be2 Be6 $15)
9... Nd7 (9... Ne4 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3) 10. Bf4 (10. f4 {restricts the own
dark-squared bishop and weakens the long diagonal.} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 b6 12. Be2
Bb7 13. Be3 c5 14. O-O-O {Perez Fungueiro, M (2231)-Musalov, R (2387) Pedrido
2003 (0-1, 43)} Kc7 {The safest square for the king.} 15. Rhg1 Rad8 16. g4 {
[%csl Rc4] White's attack looks consistent but it will be not before long that
he will create concrete threats. In the meanwhile the c4-pawn is chronically
weak.} Nb8 17. f5 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gb7a6] followed by ...Na5 and ...Ba6.})
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 b6 {The same plan as in the line above, but White has
slightly more active possibilities here.} 12. O-O-O (12. h4 Bb7 13. h5 h6 14.
Rh4 Ke7 15. Rg4 Rag8 16. Bd3 f6 $11 {Kapnisis,S (2451)-Postny,E (2606)
Heraklion 2017 (½-½, 46)} 17. exf6+ gxf6 18. Rxg8 Rxg8 19. g3 c5 20. a4 a5
$11) 12... Kc7 13. h4 Ba6 14. Rh3 h6 15. h5 c5 16. Rdd3 Rag8 17. Rdg3 Kd8 18.
Rg4 {In Alburt, L (2515)-Gligoric, S (2565) Lone Pine 1980 (1-0, 59) Black
played too passively and eventually lost. Instead, he should have chosen a
good moment to fight back on the kingside, the same as in the previous game.
For instance now:} g5 19. hxg6 fxg6 {[%cal Gg6g5] Planning ...g6-g5 with
comfortable play.} 20. Bxh6 Nxe5 21. Rgh4 Kd7 {[%csl Rc4] White's kingside
structure is better but his c4-pawn is doomed. Chances are about equal but
play remains interesting.}) (5. g3 $6 d5 {offers Black the initiative in the
center.}) 5... Qb6 $5 {A radical way of preventing d2-d4.} (5... d5 6. exd5
exd5 7. d4 {leads to a symmetrical position where to all probabilities Black
should equalize gradually, but the play is rather one-sided.}) (5... a6 6. O-O Qc7
7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb4 {is also playable, but White has better chances of
achieving some advantage than after the earlier opening of the center.}) 6. O-O
Be7 7. a3 ({The more popular but slower} 7. d3 d6 {is likely to transpose as
White has nothing better than playing a2-a3 anyway.}) 7... O-O (7... a5 {
weakens the queenside too early:} 8. Na4 (8. d3 d6 {was OK for Black in Bu, X 
(2644)-Solodovnichenko,Y (2585) Deizisau 2007 (1-0, 30)}) 8... Qc7 9. d4 cxd4
10. Nxd4 Nxe4 11. Nb5 Qb8 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qc2 {with big advance in development
for White, more than compensating for the missing pawn.}) 8. b4 $5 {The most
promising continuation.} ({Slow motion gives Black the time to consolidate:} 8.
Rb1 a5 9. d3 d6 10. h3 Nd7 {Starting the fight for the d4-square.} 11. Be3 Nde5
12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Na4 Qa7 14. Qb3 Bd7 15. Qb6 Nd4 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Qxa7 Rxa7 {
[%csl Gd7,Re2,Ge7] Black has a space advantage, two strong bishops and the
e2-bishop is passive. White needs to use his queenside majority somehow.} 18.
Nb6 Bc6 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 Bd8 21. b5 Be8 22. Nc8 Ra2 23. Bf3 Bd7 24. Nd6 Be7
25. Nxb7 (25. c5 Bxd6 26. cxd6 Ra5 27. b6 Rd8 {dooms the d-pawn as after} 28.
Rfc1 Bc6 29. Rxc6 bxc6 30. b7 {Black has} Rb5 $1 $19) 25... Bc8 26. c5 Bxb7 27.
c6 Ba8 28. Ra1 Rb2 29. Rfb1 Rxb1+ 30. Rxb1 Rc8 31. Rc1 Bd8 {with good winning
chances for Black in Malakhov,V (2695)-Yu,Y (2738) China 2016 (½-½, 87)})
8... cxb4 9. axb4 Bxb4 10. e5 Ne8 $1 {Preparing to undermine White's centre
with ...d7-d6.} (10... Ng4 $6 {places the knight on an unfavourable path:} 11.
Na4 Qc7 12. d4 $16 {Rublevsky,S (2639)-Zhang,P (2487) Shanghai 2001 (0-1, 27).}
) 11. Qb3 (11. Bb2 d6 12. d4 dxe5 13. dxe5 f6 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Bd3 Qc7 {
The start of a harmonious regrouping.} 16. Qe2 Qe7 17. h3 Bd7 {White is more
active but Black has an extra pawn and a solid position.}) 11... a5 12. Na4 Qc7
13. d4 d6 14. exd6 Nxd6 {and soon Black will get counterplay against the
hanging pawns. White's compensation for the pawn is entirely bearable for
Black.} *

