1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {The early opening of the center offers
both sides a wider choice of plans. This line is also important for the Benoni
players (1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nf3).} a6 $5 {This was recommended to me when I
first started playing the Benoni. Black makes a useful move, controlling b5
and keeping the possibility of transposing to a Hedgehog in some cases, but
also prepares ...d7-d5 in the spirit of Chapters 2 and 3. If later he plays ...
e7-e5 it will mean he has got the move ...a7-a6 for free. In some cases this
makes a difference as we will see.} (4... e6 5. g3 {leads us to a conflict of
interests, as I have analyzed these lines in my article on the Catalan.}) ({
Traditionally} 4... e5 5. Nb5 d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 {was one of Black's most
ambitious weapons, but there is a lot of theory there.}) 5. Nc3 ({After} 5. g3
{we can immediately feel the usefulness of ...a7-a6:} d5 6. Bg2 e5 7. Nf3 e4 $1
{With the pawn on a7 this would just expose Black's center, but here he has
the additional resource ...dxc4 when the pawn would be not so easy to
retrieve.} ({With the pawn on a7 the line examined in my Catalan articles goes
} 7... d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 {In this case the extra move may count as a
weakness as in some lines the queens stand on b3 and b6.}) 8. Nfd2 (8. Nd4 dxc4
$1 {This is the moment when ....a7-a6 is useful.} 9. Nc3 (9. O-O Bc5 10. Nc2
Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ng4 12. e3 f5 $17 {Hausner,I (2300)-Ghinda,M (2300) Rimavska
Sobota 1975 (1-0, 34)}) 9... Bc5 10. Be3 O-O 11. Ne6 (11. Nc2 Qe7 12. O-O Nbd7
13. a4 {0-1 (51) Moncelli,G-Bukal,V (2415) Martigny 1988} Rd8) 11... Qxd1+ 12.
Rxd1 Bxe3 13. Nxf8 Bb6 $17 {Rashkovsky,N (2510)-Suetin,A (2505) Sochi 1974 
(0-1, 36)}) 8... e3 9. fxe3 dxc4 (9... Ng4 {is premature:} 10. cxd5 Nxe3 11.
Qa4+ Nd7 12. Qe4+ Qe7 13. Nb3 $16 {Martz,W (2410)-Miles,A (2510) Lone Pine
1976 (1-0, 34)}) 10. Nxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Nc6 12. Nb6 Rb8 {Due to the weak
double pawns and the uncastled white king Black has normal compensation for
the pawn. For instance,} 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. Kc2 Bd6 $44) 5... d5
6. cxd5 (6. Bg5 e5 {leads to similar play as in Chapter 3. The differences
induced by ...a7-a6 can only favor Black.}) (6. e3 {can be met with} dxc4 (
6... e6 {would transpose to a sideline in Chapter 2.}) 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9.
O-O Nbd7 10. f3 {Veron,C (2110)-Shirazi,K (2423) Agneaux 2004 (0-1, 18)} Qb6
11. a4 e5 12. Nf5 Nc5 13. axb5 Rd8 14. Qc2 axb5 {with more pleasant play for
Black.}) (6. Nb3 dxc4 (6... e6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 {offers White a pleasant
version against the Isolani.}) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Na5 e5 (8... b5 $2 {does not
work here:} 9. g3 {Romanishin,O (2595)-Oliwa,M (2405) Katowice 1995 (1-0, 40)
and the rook gets into trouble.}) 9. Nxc4 Nc6 10. Nb6 Rb8 11. Bg5 Be6 {Once
again, as in line 9, the double pawns are not necessarily weak.} 12. Nbd5 (12.
Bxf6+ gxf6 13. O-O-O+ Ke8 14. Nbd5 f5 $11) 12... Be7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. g3 h5
15. h4 Ke8 16. O-O-O (16. Nc7+ Kf8 17. Nxe6+ fxe6 18. Bg2 f5 {and the central
pawns are rather strong.}) 16... Kf8 17. e3 Kg7) (6. Nf3 {is completely
inoffensive:} e6 $5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 Nc6 9. Be2 Bd6 {with an active version
of the Isolani.}) 6... Nxd5 7. Ndb5 ({Against} 7. Bd2 {Black has a choice
already.} e5 {Taking advantage of the fact that Ndb5 is not possible.} (7...
Nf6 {in the spirit of Chapter 2 is also possible, when ...a7-a6 is useful for
allowing a quick ...b7-b5.}) 8. Nb3 (8. Nf3 Nc6 9. g3 f6 $146 10. Bg2 Be6 $11 {
With the knight on f3 White has no way of fighting for the initiative.}) 8...
Nc6 9. g3 Be6 10. Bg2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 (11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Bxc3 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 f6
{offers Black dynamic compensation for the structural defects due to his
active bishops targeting the enemy queenside. At the same time, the white
bishop is restricted.} 14. Na5 h5 15. h4 Kf7 16. b3 c5 17. O-O Be7 18. Nc4 a5 {
with active play for Black. Taking the pawn is likely to cause White trouble:}
19. Nxa5 Ra6 20. a4 $2 Rb8 21. Rb1 Bd8 22. Nc4 Bxc4 23. bxc4 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 Rxa4
$17) 11... Qb6 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e7] Followed by ...Rd8 and ...Be7 with
comfortable play.}) 7... Nb4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Na3 b5 ({For the truth's sake I
must deviate from one of my first experiences as a Benoni player:} 9... e5 10.
g3 Be6 11. Bg2 N8c6 12. Be3 Kc7 13. O-O Rc8 (13... f6 14. Rfc1 Rc8 15. Nc2 Kb8
16. Nxb4 Bxb4 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Nd4 19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Be4 g6 21. Kg2 f5 22.
Bd3 Rhd8 $11 {Rashkovsky,N (2510)-Forintos,G (2490) Sochi 1974 (½-½, 27)})
14. Rfc1 Be7 15. Nc2 Nxc2 16. Rxc2 Kb8 17. Bb6 $6 (17. Nd5 {is likely to offer
White an improved version of the game quoted above.}) 17... Nd4 18. Rd2 Bb4 19.
Bxd4 exd4 20. Rxd4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rxc3 22. Rb1 b5 23. a4 Rhc8 24. f4 Rc1+ 25.
Rxc1 Rxc1+ 26. Kf2 Kc7 27. axb5 axb5 $15 {and the b-pawn eventually won the
game for Black in Dumitrache,D-Marin,M (2200) Bucuresti 1984 (0-1, 47)}) 10. e4
({The point with this move order is that} 10. g3 {does not work due to} Bb7)
10... e5 11. Be3 Be6 12. O-O-O+ Nd7 13. Kb1 Rc8 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 f6 16. Be2
Ke8 $11 {Karasev,V (2495)-Tseshkovsky,V (2550) Soviet Union 1976 (½-½, 43)} *

