1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d4 {This is one of the two possible attempts
at transposing to the fianchetto Queen's Indian. However, the missing c2-c4
allows Black to prevent that.} c5 {The variations examined here are quiet and
I have selected just some games between strong players to illustrate the main
ideas.} 5. c3 (5. O-O cxd4 6. Nxd4 (6. Qxd4 e6 7. c4 d6 8. Nc3 a6 {also
transposes to the main line.}) 6... Bxg2 7. Kxg2 e6 {most likely transposes to
the normal Hedgehog after c2-c4. If} 8. Nc3 d5 {Black is absolutely fine.}) (5.
dxc5 bxc5 6. O-O g6 7. c4 Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Hoping for a quick
development and strong pressure in the center.} (9. Qc2 d6 10. Rd1 Nc6 11. a3
Rb8 12. Rb1 Nd7 13. b4 cxb4 14. axb4 a5 15. bxa5 {½-½ Nyzhnyk, I (2622)
-Ashwin,J (2460) Philadelphia 2016}) 9... Ne4 $6 ({This move slightly violates
the development rules but is viable.} 9... d6 $5 10. Qc1 Re8 11. Rd1 Nbd7 12.
Bh3 Rb8 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. Bh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Bxf3 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. exf3 Ne5 $11 {
Colle,E-Gruenfeld,E Budapest 1926 (0-1, 31)}) 10. Na4 $6 (10. Qb3 $6 Nxc3 11.
bxc3 Qc7 12. Bxc5 d6 $44) (10. Nd5 $5 e6 11. Qb3 $1 Bc6 12. Rad1 Na6 13. Qc2
Re8 $5 {In view of the threat exd5 defending the knight White needs to retreat
with his knight already.}) 10... Qc7 11. Qc2 (11. Qb3 Nc6) 11... d6 12. Rad1
Nd7 13. Ne1 Nef6 (13... f5 $5) 14. b3 Nb6 15. Nc3 Rac8 16. Qc1 (16. Bg5 $5)
16... Rfd8 {/\e6, d5} 17. Bh3 Qc6 18. f3 e6 {Very soon, white's hopes
connected with the open d-file will vanish: the black center will start to
advance} 19. Nd3 a6 (19... d5 {would have been premature:} 20. Nb5 Ra8 21. Ne5)
20. Bf2 Nfd7 ({Still preparing for d6-d5 which was not possible yet:} 20... d5
21. Nxc5 dxc4 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. bxc4 Nxc4) 21. Bg2 $2 ({Missing the chance
for a normal position:} 21. e4 $8 Ne5 22. Nxe5 Bxe5) 21... d5 $17 {Damljanovic,
B (2559)-Marin,M (2557) Istanbul 2000 (0-1, 35).}) 5... g6 ({I like this more
than} 5... e6 {which is also entirely playable.}) 6. O-O (6. Qb3 {[%cal Gd4c5,
Gf3e5,Gf3g5] , threatening dxc5, but also Ne5/g5, can be parried in several
ways.} Qc8 (6... Qc7 7. Bf4 d6 8. O-O Bg7 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Ng5 d5 11. Na3 O-O
12. Rac1 Nc6 {with at least equality for Black in Stefanova, A (2515)-Jakovenko,
D (2732) Gibraltar 2016 (0-1, 33)}) 7. O-O Bg7 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. Be3 Qc8 10. c4
Nc6 11. Na3 O-O 12. Rac1 d6 13. Rfd1 Ng4 14. Bd2 Nd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Be1 Bxg2
17. Kxg2 Qc6+ 18. Kg1 Qc5 19. e3 Bg7 20. Bc3 Qh5 $15 {with lasting black
initiative, Jussupow,A (2581)-Tregubov,P (2606) Bern 2014 (0-1, 39)}) 6... Bg7
7. dxc5 (7. Bf4 O-O 8. a4 d6 9. Na3 Nbd7 10. a5 Rc8 11. axb6 axb6 12. Nb5 Bd5
13. Re1 h6 14. b3 Be4 15. Bf1 g5 16. Bd2 Ra8 $132 {Giri,A (2714)-Grischuk,A 
(2752) Beijing 2011 (½-½, 35)}) (7. Bg5 O-O 8. Nbd2 d6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. e3
Nd7 11. a4 d5 12. b4 a5 13. b5 Rc8 $132 {Carlsen,M (2857)-Grischuk,A (2754)
chess.com (blitz) 2016 (0-1, 67)}) (7. Qb3 {has no independent value and is
likely to transpose above after, say,} Qc8) ({The untested} 7. c4 {leads to a
double fianchetto Hedgehog, which is not in our main repertoire, but only after
losing a tempo with White. This is likely to allow Black counterplay against
the vulnerable c4-pawn or in the center:} cxd4 8. Qxd4 (8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2
O-O 10. Nc3 Qc8 11. b3 Qb7+ 12. f3 d5 $15 {In this kind of positions one extra
tempo is of vital importance.}) 8... Nc6 9. Qd3 (9. Qh4 {[%cal Gc1h6]} h6 {
parries Bh6 and leaves the queen exposed.}) 9... Rc8 10. Nc3 Nb4 $5 11. Qd1 O-O
(11... Rxc4 $2 12. Qb3 Qc7 13. Ne5 {[%csl Rc4] wins the exchange.}) 12. Be3 Na6
{[%csl Rc4] Attacking c4.} 13. Qa4 (13. b3 d5 {with at least equal play.})
13... Nc5 14. Bxc5 (14. Qa3 a5 $11 {[%csl Ra3] leaves the queen isolated.}) (
14. Qxa7 $2 Ra8 $19 {[%csl Ra7] traps the queen.}) 14... Rxc5 15. Qxa7 Ne4 $5 {
[%csl Ra7] The queen is somewhat out of play and the queenside is vulnerable,
offering Black at least adequate compensation for the pawn.} 16. Na4 {The only
way of trying to maintain the equality.} (16. Qxb7 $2 Nd6 17. Qa6 Ra5 $19)
16... Rxc4 17. Nxb6 Rc7 {and Black will retrieve the pawn soon (most probably
on b2), retaining an active position with two strong bishops.}) 7... bxc5 8.
Qb3 Qb6 (8... Bd5 9. c4 Bc6 {also works.}) ({But after the intermediate
exchange on c5,} 8... Qc8 9. Ne5 d5 10. c4 {offers White the initiative.}) 9.
Ne5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O 12. Nd2 d6 13. Nd3 Nc6 {Black has a
compact structure and White's incomplete development prevents him to set up
effective pressure along the a-file.} 14. Ra6 Rfc8 15. e4 Nd7 16. f4 Rab8 17.
Re1 Rb7 18. Kf3 f5 19. exf5 gxf5 20. Nc4 Kf7 {with comfotable play for Black
in Khenkin,I (2554)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2789) Riadh 2017 (0-1, 48)} *

