1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. d4 {This leads to more consistent play than in Chapter
8.} Bb7 4. c4 c5 5. d5 b5 {With respect to the Volga Gambit this loses a tempo,
but first of all it does not imply a pawn sacrifice and secondly ...bxc4
causes White more problems after preparing the bishop's development on a
different diagonal.} 6. Bg2 ({The untested} 6. cxb5 Bxd5 {followed by ...a7-a6
after completing the development offers Black comfortable play.}) (6. b3 e6 {
transposes to some sort of Blumenfeld gambit where the "extra tempo" b2-b3 is
more of a weakening move.} 7. dxe6 fxe6 8. cxb5 Be7 (8... Qa5+ $1) 9. Bg2 (9.
Nc3 $5) 9... Qa5+ {This is the point. Black simply retrieves the pawn.} 10.
Nbd2 Qxb5 11. O-O O-O 12. Nc4 d5 13. Nce5 Nbd7 14. Bb2 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Rad8 $11 {
Alekseev,E (2642)-Ehlvest,J (2535) Berlin 2015 (1-0, 58)}) ({The engines'
initial enthusiasm regarding} 6. e4 {quickly fades away after playing a few
normal moves:} Nxe4 7. Bg2 g6 8. O-O d6 9. Re1 Nf6) 6... bxc4 7. Nc3 (7. e4 {
needs to be treated with care.} d6 ({This time taking the pawn is dangerous.
First of all, Black has spent a tempo on ...bxc4 and secondly the a4-e8
diagonal is open.} 7... Nxe4 $2 8. O-O d6 9. Re1 Nf6 10. Nc3 g6 11. Qa4+ {
[%csl Rd6][%cal Re1e8] Black is simply lost as the pin along the e-file dooms
the d6-pawn. For instance} Qd7 12. Nb5 Na6 13. Nxd6+) 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. O-O g6 {
transposing to one of the lines below.}) 7... d6 8. Nd2 {White hurries to
retrieve the pawn and install the knight on an active square.} (8. Bg5 Nbd7 9.
O-O g6 10. e4 Bg7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. f4 Nb6 13. a4 a5 14. g4 h6 15. Bh4 Qd7 16.
Bh3 Nh7 17. Nf3 e6 $17 {Dang,H (2356)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2673) Ho Chi Minh
City 2017 (0-1, 46)}) ({The main alternative is ignoring the pawn and mainly
play in the center:} 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 g6 10. Bf4 (10. e5 {is interesting but
Black has enough resources:} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qa4+ Qd7 13. Qxc4 Bg7 14.
Qxc5 O-O 15. Be3 Rfb8 16. Rfd1 Ne8 17. Qa5 Nd6 $11 {With an improved version
of the typical Gruenfeld blockade on d6 as the e7-pawn contributes to the
stability, Sarana,A (2464)-Gordievsky,D (2596) Moscow 2017 (0-1, 46)}) 10...
Nh5 $5 $146 {A multi-purpose move. First of all, Black rids himself of the
danger posed by e4-e5. Secondly, the knight can later go to g7 after the
predictable bishops exchange, thus sustaining ...f7-f5.} ({The natural} 10...
Nb6 {is likely to conceal White the initiative. The point is that the knight
does not have perspectives on b6.} 11. Qd2 Bg7 12. Rad1 O-O 13. Bh6 Re8 14.
Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rfe1 Qc7 16. Nh4 {with attacking chances in Naumkin, I (2437)
-Rozum,I (2601) Moscow 2017 (0-1, 43)}) 11. Be3 Bg7 12. Qd2 ({If} 12. Nd2 Nb6 {
already makes sense, as White does not have the plan of exchanging the bishops
anymore.}) 12... O-O 13. Bh6 Rb8 14. Bxg7 (14. Ne1 Bc8 15. Rb1 Bxh6 16. Qxh6
Ne5 {We see here that the knight has better paths than on b6.}) 14... Nxg7 15.
Ne1 (15. Rfe1 f6 {followed by ...Ne5.}) 15... f5 {with counterplay.}) 8... g6
9. Nxc4 Bg7 10. Qa4+ {The only attempt to spoil Black's harmony.} (10. O-O O-O
11. Re1 Ba6 12. Qa4 (12. Ne3 Nbd7 13. Qc2 Rb8 14. Rb1 e5 $5 15. b3 Nb6 16. Nf1
Nh5 17. e4 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Bb2 Qg5 $36 {Hulak,K (2510)-Timman,J (2610)
Sarajevo 1984 (0-1, 73)}) 12... Bxc4 13. Qxc4 Nbd7 14. Rb1 Qa5 15. a3 Rab8 16.
Bd2 Ne5 17. Qa2 {In Aronian,L (2784)-Zvjaginsev,V (2660) Berlin 2015 (1-0, 37)
Black had achieved a normal Volga Gambit position, with the differences that
pawns were equal. He should have continued his queenside plan with} c4 {
Planning ...Rb3.} 18. b4 cxb3 19. Rxb3 Rxb3 20. Qxb3 Nfd7 {with at least equal
play.}) 10... Qd7 (10... Nbd7 11. Na5 {is a bit molesting.}) 11. Qc2 (11. Qxd7+
Nbxd7 12. Na5 Ba6 13. O-O Nb6 14. Nc6 Bc4 15. Rd1 a5 16. a4 (16. e4 Nfd7 {
possibly followed by ...Ne5 or ...Nb8.}) 16... Bb3 {The knight on c6 is not
that molesting and otherwise Black has an entirely normal play.}) 11... O-O 12.
Na5 (12. O-O Ba6 13. b3 Qc7 14. Bd2 Nbd7 15. h3 Nb6 $11 {(½-½, 66)Illner,A 
(2472)-Poetsch,H (2489) Belgium 2015}) 12... Qc7 $146 (12... Na6 {puts the
knight on an unfavourable path.} 13. O-O Rab8 14. Bg5 $14 {Esipenko,A (2564)
-Duda,J (2717) Riadh 2017 (0-1, 55)}) (12... Ba6 $5 13. O-O Qc7 14. Qa4 Re8 {
Defending the e7-pawn before White attacks it.} 15. Bf4 Nbd7 16. Nc6 Bb7 {
followed by ...Nb6, when the knight's stability on c6 is questionable.}) 13.
Nxb7 Qxb7 14. O-O Nbd7 $11 *

