1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 5. d3 $5 {In this and the next line
we examine White's plan based on e2-e4, something completely different with
respect to everything seen so far.} (5. b3 Be7 6. Bb2 c5 {most likely
transposes to the Hedgehog.}) ({The same goes for} 5. d4 c5) 5... c5 6. e4 d6
7. Nc3 (7. c4 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 {transposes to Chapter 1.}) ({The general opinion
is that} 7. b3 {does not suit the KI attack too well.} Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2 (
9. c4 Nfd7 $5 $146 10. Qe2 Nc6 11. d4 e5 $11) 9... Nc6 10. Re1 Nd7 {Black
immediately starts to neutralize the bishop's latent pressure. In case of
exchanging it, White will be left with queenside weaknesses.} ({But there are
worthy alternatives.} 10... b5 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qb6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. c4 a6
{with a comfortable Scheveningen Sicilian in Cabrilo, G (2477)-Sedlak, N (2556)
Jahorina 2012 (½-½, 34)}) (10... Qc7 11. Rc1 Nd7 12. c3 Nde5 13. Qc2 Ba6 14.
Re3 {Radovici,C (2345)-Stoica,V (2460) Baile Tusnad 1997 (0-1, 52)} Ng4 $11)
11. Nc4 (11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 {Minasian,A (2570)-Nedobora,M 
(2435) Oviedo 1993 (0-1, 65)} Qc7 14. Nf1 Rac8 15. c4 Bf6 16. Ne3 a6 $11 {
with a comfortable Hedgehog.}) 11... b5 12. Ne3 Bf6 13. c3 (13. Qc1 Bxb2 14.
Qxb2 Qf6 15. Qc1 a6 16. Qd2 Nde5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 $11 {Tsydypov,Z (2523)-Lysyj,I 
(2618) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017 (0-1, 44)}) 13... Nde5 14. Qd2 a5 15. d4 Nxf3+ 16.
Bxf3 a4 {with good counterplay in a complex position, Florean, A (2441)
-Simantsev,M (2403) Bucharest 2000 (½-½ 64)}) (7. Nbd2 {is examined in
Chapter 11}) (7. Nh4 {does not have much independent value either, as White
would have to develop his queen's knight soon while his kingside attack is not
too dangerous before Black has castled.} Nc6 8. f4 Be7 {. The same goes for
moves like 7.Re1 or 7.Qe2. Black should continue in the spirit of the main
lines examined below.}) 7... Be7 8. Ne1 {The start of a slow but consistent
kingside attack.} (8. Re1 a6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {reaches an inoffensive
Scheveningen setup with a tempo less for White.} Qc7 11. g4 (11. a4 Nc6 12.
Nde2 O-O 13. h3 Rfd8 14. Nf4 Rac8 15. Nd3 Nd7 16. Ne2 Nce5 17. Nd4 Nc5 $11 {
Damljanovic,B (2596)-Sedlak,N (2553) Vrsac 2008 (0-1, 69)}) 11... O-O ({
Caution is needed:} 11... Nc6 $2 12. g5 Nd7 13. Nf5 exf5 $2 14. Nd5 Qd8 15.
exf5 $16) 12. g5 Nfd7 13. a4 Re8 ({The careless} 13... Nc6 {allowed} 14. Nd5 $1
$14 {in Tosic,M (2416)-Zivkovic,N (2198) Nis 2012 (0-1, 33) as the bishop is
hanging after the opening of the e-file.}) 14. f4 Nc6 $11) (8. Nh4 {can be met
in similar way as the main plan:} Nc6 (8... Nfd7 9. f4 Bxh4 10. gxh4 Qxh4 {
allows} 11. Nb5 $1) 9. f4 Qd7) 8... Nc6 9. f4 Qd7 $5 $146 {In most games Black
castles short early. I believe the untested suggested move is better, as it
keeps the possibility of castling long if White commits himself too much on
the kingside.} 10. Bd2 (10. g4 O-O-O 11. g5 Ne8 {allows Black to open the
kingside with dangerous counterplay.}) (10. Be3 {exposes the bishop to} d5 11.
e5 d4 $1) ({The flexible} 10. Nf3 {delays g3-g4 so Black can already play} O-O
({Instead,} 10... O-O-O 11. a3 {could be dangerous as Black's kingside play is
not that obvious.}) 11. h3 Rad8 12. g4 Ne8 13. g5 Nc7 14. h4 f5 $11) 10...
O-O-O 11. a3 h5 {The play is likely to become sharp. Here is just an
illustrative line:} 12. Nf3 Ne8 (12... d5 13. Ne5 Qe8 {is also worth a try.})
13. b4 h4 14. Rb1 Nd4 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Ne2 hxg3 17. hxg3 Bf6 18. c4 dxc3 19.
Bxc3 Bxc3 20. Nxc3 Kb8 {with good play for Black.} *

