1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 {Here we will
include lines which, with the possible exception of the main one, do not
require separate examination.} 7. d3 $5 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qc7 {
is likely to transpose to familiar positions.} 10. Bg5 (10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 {
is an exact transposition to a line which was dealt with in the first database.
}) (10. Qd3 Nc6 $11) 10... Be7 11. Rc1 Nc6 $11) (7. e3 Be7 8. d4 O-O 9. d5 ({
Trying to prevent ...b6-b5 in advance with} 9. a4 {allows Black to change
plans:} cxd4 10. exd4 d5 11. Ne5 Ra7 12. b3 dxc4 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. bxc4 Rc7
$132) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 d6 {We have reached a pseudo-Benoni. The move e2-e3
is rather harmful for White as he does not have Bf4. Black's bishop is on e7
instead of g7, but could later emerge on f6. But the main point is that ...
b6-b5 is inevitable for instance} 11. a4 b5 {, meaning that Black has
reasonable play.}) 7... Be7 ({After spending a tempo on ...a7-a6 Black cannot
transpose to Chapter 1 with} 7... d6 8. e4 g6 {due to} 9. d4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 $1 {
with problems on d6.}) 8. e4 d6 {This was the position Black can avoid in
Chapter 1, but the good news is that it remains playable.} 9. Ne1 (9. d4 $6
cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 {reaches a normal Hedgehog with a tempo less for White (Re1).
}) (9. Nh4 {runs into} Nfd7 {as if} 10. Qg4 $2 g5 11. Nf3 h5 {wins material.})
(9. Ng5 {is the alternative way of preparing the advance of the f-pawn.} Nc6
10. f4 Nd7 11. h4 Bf6 12. f5 Qe7 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Bh3 Nd4 (14... Nd8 {avoids
the complications retaining a safe position.} 15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qg4 Ne5 $11) 15.
Ne2 Bc8 16. Nxd4 (16. e5 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 Nxe5 18. Bf4 {may offer White some
light initiative for the pawn.}) 16... Bxd4+ 17. Kh2 Nf6 18. Nf3 O-O 19. Nxd4
cxd4 20. Bg5 e5 21. Bxc8 Raxc8 22. Qe2 Qe6 23. Bxf6 Rxf6 24. Rxf6 Qxf6 25. Rf1
{In Macieja,B (2622)-Flores,D (2512) Buenos Aires 2006 (1-0, 40) Black should
have avoided Qg4 with} Qe6 $11 {[%cal Gb6b5] possibly followed by ...b6-b5.})
9... Nc6 10. f4 O-O ({The exotic} 10... h5 $5 {trying to fight back on the
kingside also deserves mentioning.} 11. Nf3 Nd7 12. Be3 h4 13. a3 hxg3 14. hxg3
Nf6 15. Ne1 g5 16. f5 Ne5 17. Bxg5 Nfg4 18. Bf4 Bf6 19. Nc2 Ke7 20. fxe6 fxe6
21. Ne3 Qg8 {with a dangerous attack in Anastasian,A (2593)-Sargissian,G (2600)
Yerevan 2003 (0-1, 38)}) 11. g4 $5 Nd7 12. Nf3 e5 13. g5 $5 (13. f5 $6 Nd4 {
takes over the control on the dark squares.}) 13... exf4 (13... Nd4 $5) 14.
Bxf4 Nde5 15. Qd2 Nxf3+ 16. Rxf3 f6 $5 {Fighting back on the kingside before
the attack becomes real.} (16... Ne5 $5) (16... Nd4) 17. g6 {A thematic but
concretely insufficient attempt to keep the tension.} (17. Nd5 Nd4 18. Nxe7+ (
18. Rff1 Bxd5 $5 19. gxf6 Bxf6 20. exd5 Ra7 $15) 18... Qxe7 19. Rff1 f5 $5 $11)
17... hxg6 18. Bh3 f5 (18... Nd4 19. Rg3 g5 20. Be3 f5 {looks even stronger.})
19. Rg3 Nd4 20. Kh1 g5 $1 21. Bxg5 Bxg5 22. Qxg5 Qxg5 23. Rxg5 fxe4 24. dxe4
Rae8 $15 {Dzindzichashvili,R (2550)-Browne,W (2550) Tilburg 1978 (½-½, 39).}
*

